abstract = {We analyze global climate model predictions of soil temperature (from the Coupled Model In- 6 tercomparison Project 5 (CMIP5) database) to assess the models' representation of current- 7 climate soil thermal dynamics, and their predictions of permafrost thaw during the 21st 8 century. We compare the models' predictions to observations of active layer thickness, air 9 temperature, and soil temperature, and to theoretically-expected relationships between ac- 10 tive layer thickness and air temperature annual mean and seasonal cycle amplitude. Models 11 show a wide range of current permafrost areas, active layer statistics (cumulative distribu- 12 tions, correlations with mean annual air temperature and amplitude of seasonal air temper- 13 ature cycle), and ability to accurately model the coupling between soil and air temperatures 14 at high latitudes. Many of the between-model differences can be traced to differences in the 15 coupling between either near-surface air and shallow soil temperatures, or between shallow 16 and deeper (1m) soil temperatures, which in turn reflect differences in snow physics and soil 17 hydrology. We compare the models to observational datasets to benchmark the permafrost- 18 relevant physics of the models. The models show a wide range of predictions for permafrost 19 loss: 2-66{\%} for RCP2.6, 15-87{\%} for RCP4.5, and 30-99{\%} for RCP8.5. Normalizing the 20 amount of permafrost loss by the amount of high-latitude warming in the RCP4.5 scenario, 21 the models predict an absolute loss of 1.6 ± 0.7 million km2 permafrost ◦C−1 high-latitude 22 warming, or a fractional loss of 6-29 {\%} ◦ C−1 .},
