{\textgreater}{\textgreater} There are ways around this: see Illman and Neuman (2000) and an alternative method published by Kuusela-Lahtinen et al (2003)
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Using just a pneumatic/hydraulic test is possible to define fracture aperture if the tests is paired with a theoretical model (e.g. effective hydraulic aperture, see Folger et al 1999)
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} This is based on the cubic law
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater}Which is a little problematic in the real world. Corrections for roughness and fully continuous and open fractures need to be implemented for the cubic law to be an effective tool in characterizing 
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Film flow can occur in very small or large fractures and is strongly enhanced by surface roughness, the film may exceed mean velocities by multiple orders of magnitude

Dynamic Natuer of Flow Channels
- There are preferred flow paths for fluids through fractures which is determined by asperities and aperture variation throughout the fracture
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} These variations in asperities and apertures have been determined by careful measurements
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Within a millimeter, the measurements of asperities and apertures may vary by orders of magnitude, thus the interest in fine resolutions
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} There exists evidence from field studies that preferred paths are present on scales larger than a single fracture
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Meaning that the intersection of fractures could play a role in creating preferred paths of flow

Implications vis-a-vis Conceptualization of Fractured Rocks as Discrete Networs
