@article{Steefel2009,
annote = {----Introduction----
- Fluid-Rock interaction (FRI) were treated thermodynamically, equilibrium was assumed between fluid and rock
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} This treateed FRIs as static
- Helgeson introduced the idea of an irreversible reaction and treated FRIs as dynamically evolving systems of multiple components
- Halgeson used real-time kinetics instead of reaction progress (as independent variable)
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Reaction pathway as an independent variable is helpful when considering closed systems but when transport is the driving force behind the system, as is the case in many Earth Science scenarios, real-time is far more helpfull 
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} in the 1980s, Lichtner clarified this idea by taking a Lagrangian look at these reactions. His work conceptualized the FRIs with pure advection, which meant that he followed the reactions as a packet of fluid travled through the rock medium
- Multi-Cpmponent Reactive Transport models (MC-RTM) sprung into being in the early 1980s with work by Berner, Lichtner, Yeh and Tripathi, and Steefel and Lasaga
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} These were contiuum based models: models that treat media as whole or continous rather than a collection of aggregate pieces, thus spatio-temporal scale is important (i.e. you need to know the REV)

----Transport Processes----
-***The most important factors to understand w/ transport processes are 1) advection, 2) molecular diffusion and mechanical dispersion 
- Batch System: time scale where the net reaction rates are effectively zero, equilibrium is achieved (????What exactly is this???)
- Open System: author provides a laboratory example of a continuously stirred tank reactor (CSTR)
[Point 1 of First Paragraph]
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} In this example, a fluid is continously injected inside a reactor. This fluid is either in disequlibrium with itself or with the solid inside the reactor. The product that flows through the reactor reaches a steady-state, often at some distance away from equlibrium
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} We can characterize this steady state behavior by the ratio of the fluid residence time (tau{\_}res) to the reaction time (tau{\_}react) [Equation 001]
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater} However, realistic examples are more complex than the CSTR example, fluids are not injected at the same rate and the conditions of the medium change with space and usually with time as well
---{\%}Advection{\%}---
- Defined: The translation of space of dissolved/suspended material at the rate of movement of the bulk fluid phase
- Mathematically, a purely advected substance through porous media has an advective flux (J{\_}adv) equal to the porosity (phi) * average linear velocity of the fluid (v), and the concentration of the species in question (C{\_}i) [Equation 002] 
- [Equations 003-006] are used to explain Darcian Flow, or how to calculate the linear velocity in [Equation 002]
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} In sum, the velocity depends on the permeability, hydraulic head, fluid viscosity, and fluid density
{\textgreater}{\textgreater}{\textgreater}***Darcian flow only works with continuous mediums as opposed to pore scale flow, where the variability is too great***
---{\%}Molecular Diffusion{\%}---
- Pure advection is rarely observed in FRIs, thus diffusion of the solutes is important to characterize
- Diffusion is often described with Fickean rules (however, the authors point out that these only apply with dilute and uncharged species)
{\textgreater}{\textgreater} Mathematically, the diffusive flux of the solute (J{\_}i) equaled to the negative of the diffusive coefficient multiplied by the change in concentration of the solute with respect to the change in location of the solute (Fick's 1st Law) [Equation 007]
